In Week 2 of Trump\'92s second term, the pattern that emerged was not of a government settling into routine, but of a government moving fast to change what \'93routine\'94 will mean. The week\'92s core theme was consolidation: of power in the executive, of loyalty as the main currency inside the state, and of fear as a tool against those outside it. The moves were not only loud, like tariffs and mass raids, but also quiet, like the deletion of databases and the rewriting of handbooks. Together they showed a governing project that treats law as an instrument, not a boundary, and treats whole classes of people as contingent members of the political community. This was a week in which the architecture of oversight, civil service, and citizenship itself was deliberately weakened.\
\
At the close of Week 1, the Democracy Clock stood at 7:55 p.m. By the end of Week 2, it read 8:03 p.m., an advance of 8.6 minutes. That is a large move this early in a term. The shift came from several linked changes. The presidency tested and, in some domains, breached the limits of congressional control over money. Inspectors general and other watchdogs were fired in clusters, often in open defiance of statutory notice rules. The civil service was pushed toward a loyalty system through new categories, mass resignation offers, and data grabs. Law enforcement and immigration powers were turned sharply toward political and ideological ends, while the meaning of citizenship was attacked through orders on birthright, status, and detention. Courts did push back on some of the most sweeping fiscal and citizenship moves, but their interventions slowed rather than reversed the trend. The clock moved because the week made it harder to imagine a quick return to a system in which law, not will, sets the outer edge of power.\
\
One of the clearest developments was the assault on independent oversight. Over a few days, the president dismissed between fifteen and eighteen inspectors general across major departments, including Defense, State, Transportation, Agriculture, and Health and Human Services. Some were physically escorted from their offices. The firings came without the 30 days\'92 written notice and reasons that Congress had required in the 2022 inspector general independence law. Senator Chuck Grassley, a Republican long associated with oversight, reported that the White House had not answered his inquiries. The pattern was not a single disputed removal but a purge. It stripped agencies of internal auditors and investigators whose job is to surface waste, fraud, and abuse. When those roles are emptied or filled with loyalists, the public loses a key line of defense against corruption, and honest officials inside the system lose allies.\
\
The same impulse appeared in the labor sphere. The administration fired the general counsel and the chair of the National Labor Relations Board, as well as Democratic appointees to the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, even though they had years left in their terms and statutory protections against removal without cause. Former NLRB chairs called the moves unprecedented and illegal. With the NLRB left without a quorum, the federal body charged with enforcing collective bargaining rights could not issue major decisions. At the same time, the president disbanded the EEOC altogether in one account, and in another fired its Democratic leadership. These actions did more than change personnel. They disabled the machinery that workers use to challenge unfair practices and discrimination. When the agencies that enforce rights are hollowed out, rights on paper become promises without teeth.\
\
Alongside the purge of watchdogs came a coordinated effort to politicize the civil service. The Office of Personnel Management issued guidance for a new \'93Schedule Policy/Career,\'94 reviving and extending the earlier Schedule F concept. Under this plan, tens of thousands of career officials could be reclassified into roles where they could be fired at will for failing to follow presidential directives. The message was blunt: executive branch employees must carry out the president\'92s agenda or lose their jobs. In parallel, White House teams began visiting agencies to screen applicants for loyalty and enthusiasm for Trump\'92s program. This was not about a handful of senior posts; it reached into the ranks that had long been insulated from partisan swings. The reach was wide and deliberate.\
\
The pressure was not only formal. Nearly three million federal workers received emails offering them \'93deferred resignations\'94 effective at the end of September, with the promise of months of pay if they left and the warning of layoffs or reassignments if they stayed. Another message, reportedly driven by Elon Musk\'92s team now embedded at OPM, offered inducements to resign that surprised even the White House. More than 1,100 Environmental Protection Agency employees were told they were now on probationary status and could be fired immediately. At the Department of Veterans Affairs, the directors of the Center for Women Veterans and the Center for Minority Veterans were dismissed. At the Treasury Department, the highest\uc0\u8209 ranking career official, David Lebryk, retired after resisting Musk allies\'92 demands for access to sensitive payment systems. These moves, taken together, signaled that neutrality and expertise were no longer shields. The state\'92s permanent staff were being sorted into loyal and expendable.\
