Law itself was bent to favor allies and punish out\uc0\u8209 groups. On his first day back in office, Trump issued mass clemency for roughly 1,500 people charged or convicted in the January 6 attack, including those who assaulted police. Stewart Rhodes, the Oath Keepers leader convicted of seditious conspiracy, received a pardon and soon appeared at a Trump rally in Las Vegas. Federal judges, noting the commutations, lifted conditions that had barred Rhodes and others from entering Washington, DC and the Capitol. The Department of Justice opened a \'93special project\'94 to review its own handling of January 6 cases. At the same time, the department fired more than a dozen prosecutors who had worked on criminal cases against Trump, including members of Special Counsel Jack Smith\'92s team, and later moved to fire dozens of FBI agents who had investigated January 6. Cases against Trump\'92s co\u8209 defendants in the classified documents probe were closed. The pattern was clear. Those who had attacked the transfer of power were forgiven and welcomed back into political life. Those who had investigated the president and his circle were removed.\
