Against this backdrop, Congress and the president together hardened the law against immigrants. The Laken Riley Act, signed into law this week, mandated detention of undocumented immigrants charged with theft\uc0\u8209 related crimes and gave state attorneys general standing to sue the federal government for alleged failures to enforce immigration law. The administration also invoked the Alien Enemies Act of 1798 to target undocumented immigrants, justifying it with claims of a crime wave that were contradicted by independent studies. Temporary Protected Status for Venezuelans was rescinded, and deportation protections for more than 600,000 Venezuelans were revoked. These measures did not simply tighten enforcement; they created a two\u8209 tier system in which some people\'92s liberty depended on their origin and status, and in which accusation alone could trigger detention.\
