The meaning of citizenship itself came under direct attack. On his first day, Trump signed an executive order purporting to end birthright citizenship for children born in the United States to non\uc0\u8209 citizen parents. The order threw thousands of expecting parents into uncertainty, with some fearing their children would be stateless. At least twenty\u8209 two state attorneys general filed lawsuits arguing that the order violated the Fourteenth Amendment. A federal judge in Seattle, and later another judge referenced in national coverage, temporarily blocked the order, preserving birthright citizenship while litigation proceeds. Yet the attempt mattered in its own right. It signaled that the administration was willing to reinterpret a core constitutional guarantee by decree and normalized the idea that citizenship can be stratified by heritage and ideology.\
