Emergency powers and security rhetoric were used to justify extraordinary measures. The president declared a state of emergency at the southern border and signed a series of orders reversing prior immigration policies. These orders allowed arrests in schools, churches, and hospitals, locations that had long been treated as sensitive. ICE was given sharply increased arrest quotas\'971,200 to 1,500 per day in one directive, 1,800 in another\'97with each field office assigned daily targets. Raids in Chicago and other cities, involving ICE, the FBI, the DEA, and U.S. Marshals, led to hundreds of arrests and widespread fear. Indigenous Americans and even Puerto Rican citizens were detained and questioned. Homeland Security Secretary Kristi Noem donned tactical gear and joined dawn raids in New York City, operations reportedly staged for television. A Space Force base in Colorado was opened for processing and detaining migrants. Plans were announced, and then formalized by executive order, to prepare a 30,000\uc0\u8209 person migrant detention facility at Guant\'e1namo Bay. Migrants were described as \'93the worst criminal illegal aliens threatening the American people.\'94 The language of war and emergency was being applied to civil immigration enforcement.\
