By the end of Week 2, with the clock at 8:03 p.m., the story of Trump\'92s second term had moved from campaign promises to structural change. The week mattered because it showed how quickly a determined executive can reshape the terrain on which democracy rests. Inspectors general and civil servants, once dull guardians of continuity, were revealed as central targets. Law enforcement and immigration tools, once bounded by norms about sensitive locations and proportionality, were recast as instruments of spectacle and fear. Citizenship, once a birthright, was treated as a policy variable. Memory, once anchored in archives and curricula, was pruned to fit the needs of those in power. Courts and civil society did not stand still, but their victories were defensive and partial.\
