The Democracy Clock does not measure outrage; it measures capacity. After this week, the capacity of institutions to check the presidency, to protect neutral administration, and to treat all persons within the jurisdiction as equal before the law was weaker than before. The capacity of the executive to act quickly, to reward allies and punish enemies, and to rewrite the stories the state tells about itself was stronger. That is why the time moved forward. At 8:03 p.m., there is still daylight in the metaphorical sky, but the shadows are longer, and the work required to turn back the hands has grown.\
